I sit with hands calmly on the grand piano, just in front of the pews I was doing math problems in a few Sundays ago. I barely peer at my score and happily play The First Noel. The congregation applauded. How could I cry or whine? I am the child excited for Santa Claus this Tuesday. 

We adore the interviewee. He likes us. ‚ÄúI don‚Äôt understand your vision statement.‚Äù I suspect the last time it has been updated I was not in this world. The interview ends and we begin to address the problem. I thought of the vision statement work I have done in robotics. Staring at this outdated document, I slowly edge my cursor to the unmute button. ‚ÄúI can rewrite the vision and mission statement.‚Äù As if God has given me breath, I started to speak. Without thinking, I explained what was wrong with the current mission and vision statement. They received my digital illustration. I did something. I had experience and use it. I am the teenager finally contributing to the committee.

I am the child crying every day except Wednesday. I am the annoyance, the whining child interrupting the spirituality of Pastor Wilson‚Äôs lengthy sermons. I am ruining it for everyone else. 

I‚Äôm on a Zoom call with the same people who remember me as a sobbing child. The same people who are young enough to try new technology, yet old enough to not be able to figure it out after using it for a year. ‚ÄúHow do I start the recording? Can you do it William?‚Äù I start the recording and my focus ends. How does the pastor search process work anyways? I am the child lost in the Zoom call with angry elders. 

I squirm in the pew filled with anxiety. I want to go home. My dad sees my eyes well, about to burst into a tantrum. He scribbles in his notebook comfortingly. He gifts me a set of math problems. I fill them out satisfyingly and beg for more. 

An interview, yes! Now we can fill the void of not having a permanent pastor. The committee must prepare for the interview. We crawled through the questions of what seemed to be from the old, failed search committee. ‚ÄúWhat is your understanding of how LGBTQ members should be treated in as church that is open and not affirming?‚Äù Pause. Even the static of the microphones went silent. I felt eleven pairs of old eyes glare at me through my laptop screen. 7:38, 7:39, 7:40 passes in the corner of my monitor. ‚ÄúCan you do it William?‚Äù Is this what I am? The person who does the task no one wants to do. I feel powerless, like a child facing adversity. I‚Äôm in a place where everyone should have a say, yet I can‚Äôt speak. My voice is not important. I am the child who can‚Äôt say no.
